title="Abstract Algebra">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Section 0.2</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, we may write it as a product
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[n=p_{1}^{\alpha _{1}}(…)p_{k}^{\alpha _{k}}]]></fr:tex>
of distinct primes <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p_{i}]]></fr:tex> and exponents <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{i}\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>. Here "uniqueness" means if we have another factorization
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[n=q_{1}^{\beta _{1}}(…)q_{\ell }^{\beta _{\ell }},]]></fr:tex>
then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k=\ell ]]></fr:tex> and we have a bijection <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma \colon \{1,…,k\}\to \{1,…,\ell \}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p_{i}=q_{\sigma (i)}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{i}=\beta _{\sigma (i)}]]></fr:tex>. In other words, the two factorizations differ only in the ordering of factors.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
