type="local"
href="alex-nelson.xml"
addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Primitive</html:dfn> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n^{\text {th}}]]></fr:tex> roots of unity are the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\zeta \in \mu _{n}]]></fr:tex> such that they generate the group <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle \zeta \rangle =\mu _{n}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>The <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n^{\text {th}}]]></fr:tex> <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Cyclotomic Polynomial</html:dfn> is defined as
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\Phi _{n}(x)=\prod _{\substack {\zeta \in \mu _{n}\\\zeta \text { primitive}}}(x-\zeta ).]]></fr:tex></fr:p><fr:p><fr:strong>Exercise 1:</fr:strong> When <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> is prime, prove every element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mu _{p}]]></fr:tex> is primitive.</fr:p><fr:p><fr:strong>Exercise 2:</fr:strong> When <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> is prime, prove
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\Phi _{p}(x)=\frac {x^{p}-1}{x-1}=x^{p-1}+x^{p-2}+…+x+1.]]></fr:tex></fr:p><fr:p><fr:strong>Exercise 3:</fr:strong> Prove <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (\Phi _{n}(x))=\phi (n)]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi (n)]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-0005.xml"
addr="nt-0005"
title="Euler totient">Euler totient</fr:link> function.</fr:p><fr:p><fr:strong>Exercise 4:</fr:strong> Prove
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[x^{n}-1=\sum _{\zeta \in \mu _{n}}(x-\zeta )=\prod _{d\mathrel {\bigm |} n}\prod _{\text {prim }\zeta \in \mu _{d}}(x-\zeta )=\prod _{d\mathrel {\bigm |} n}\Phi _{d}(x).]]></fr:tex></fr:p><fr:p><fr:strong>Exercise 5:</fr:strong> Prove <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{4}(x)=x^{2}+1]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{6}(x)=x^{2}-x+1]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{8}(x)=x^{4}+1]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{9}(x)=x^{6}+x^{3}+1]]></fr:tex>. (Hint: use exercise 4 and calculate <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{n}-1]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n=4,6,8,9]]></fr:tex>.)</fr:p><fr:p><fr:strong>Caution:</fr:strong> it is false that all coefficients of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{n}(x)]]></fr:tex> are <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\pm 1]]></fr:tex> or 0. But the first counter-example appears at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n=105]]></fr:tex> which has two terms with coefficient <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[-2]]></fr:tex>. However, it is true that all coefficients of every Cyclotomic polynomial are integers.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
