title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The proof is based loosely on two ideas:
<fr:ol><fr:li>We may compare the factorization of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{n}-1]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> with that of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{n}-1]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}_{p}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\nmid  n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
<fr:li>Investigate how automorphisms of a finite field permute the roots of polynomials.</fr:li></fr:ol>
More about the second idea: suppose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F(x)]]></fr:tex> is a polynomial over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}_{p}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F(x)=f(x)g(x)]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x),g(x)\in \mathbb {F}_{p}[x]]]></fr:tex>. The splitting field of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F(x)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}_{p^{n}}]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, and the Frobenius morphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi (x)=x^{p}]]></fr:tex> is an automorphism of this splitting field. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi ]]></fr:tex> is the identity function on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}_{p}]]></fr:tex>, it must permute the roots of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F(x)]]></fr:tex>. Suppose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex> is a root of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F(x)]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi (\alpha )=\alpha ^{p}]]></fr:tex> is a root of either <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)]]></fr:tex>. But <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(\alpha ^{p})=g(\alpha )^{p}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(\alpha ^{p})=0]]></fr:tex> implies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(\alpha )=0]]></fr:tex>. So if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F(x)]]></fr:tex> is separable, then the Frobenius morphism permutes the roots of different factors of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F(x)]]></fr:tex> separately.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Studying how automorphisms of a splitting field for a polynomial acts on the roots of the polynomial naturally leads to Galois theory.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
